        <svcproc svcproctype="repair" graphiccount="3">
            <title>SERVICE PROCEDURE</title>
            <para>The following procedure should be followed to determine and correct caliper wear and select the proper
                shim to reduce the bumper gap. Refer to hydraulic brake section CTS-5009 in the CTS-5000 Master Service
                Manual for additional service information and specifications.
            </para>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Remove the support key retaining bolt and tap the support key and spring out of the
                    V-way between the caliper and anchor plate (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9204011">Figure 1</hotlnk>). Remove the caliper from the anchor plate.
                </para>
                <figure id="f9204011" figsize="pg-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../tsifigures/g9204011.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 1. Disc Brake Components</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. CALIPER ASSEMBLY</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. V-WAY SURFACE</callout1>
                        <callout1>3. SHIM</callout1>
                        <callout1>4. SUPPORT SPRING</callout1>
                        <callout1>5. RETENTION BOLT</callout1>
                        <callout1>6. SUPPORT KEY</callout1>
                        <callout1>7. ANCHOR PLATE</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Clean the V-way surfaces of the caliper and anchor plate with a wire brush. Use a file
                    to remove any deep nicks and/or gouges.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Lay a straight edge across the caliper V-way surfaces as shown in
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9204012">Figure 2</hotlnk>and measure the wear on these surfaces with a feeler
                    gauge.
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Calipers that display wear of .050 inch or greater must be replaced.</para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
                <figure id="f9204012" figsize="col-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../tsifigures/g9204012.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 2. Measuring Caliper Wear</caption>
                    <calloutgroup>
                        <callout1>1. STRAIGHT EDGE</callout1>
                        <callout1>2. FEELER GAUGE</callout1>
                    </calloutgroup>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Re-install the caliper on the anchor plate. Temporarily install a new support key
                    (centered in the V-way) (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9204013">Figure 3</hotlnk>). DO NOT INSTALL THE SUPPORT SPRING. Secure the key to
                    the caliper with the support key retaining bolt.
                </para>
                <figure id="f9204013" figsize="pg-wide">
                    <graphic filename="../tsifigures/g9204013.webp" type="webp"/>
                    <caption>Figure 3. Bumper Gap Dimension</caption>
                </figure>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Insert a suitable pry tool (large screwdriver) between the caliper and the support key
                    and pry firmly to assure that the caliper is seated against the three surfaces "A", "B", and "C" (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9204013">Figure 3</hotlnk>).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Measure bumper gap (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9204013">Figure 3</hotlnk>) formed between the support key and caliper using a
                    feeler gauge or stack of feeler gauges.
                </para>
                <specpara>
                    <note>
                        <para>Make this measurement on one side of the pry instrument and then the other.</para>
                    </note>
                </specpara>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">If the bumper gap (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9204013">Figure 3</hotlnk>) measures more than .058 inch, select the proper size
                    shim from
                    <hotlnk xrefid="t9204012">Table 2</hotlnk>.
                </para>
                <table id="t9204012" frame="all">
                    <tgroup cols="2" colsep="1" rowsep="1">
                        <colspec colname="col1" colwidth="3.17in"/>
                        <colspec colname="col2" colwidth="3.00in"/>
                        <spanspec namest="col1" nameend="col2" spanname="1to2"/>
                        <thead>
                            <row>
                                <entry colspan="2" spanname="1to2" valign="top" align="center">
                                    <para>
                                        <emph type="bold">Bumper Gap Measurement/Shim Size Number</emph>
                                    </para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry valign="top" align="center">
                                    <para>
                                        <emph type="bold">Bumper Gap Measurement</emph>
                                    </para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry valign="top" align="center">
                                    <para>
                                        <emph type="bold">Use Shim Number</emph>
                                    </para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                        </thead>
                        <tbody>
                            <row>
                                <entry valign="top" align="center">
                                    <para>.005 to .058 inch</para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry valign="top" align="center">
                                    <para>No shim required</para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry valign="top" align="center">
                                    <para>.059 to .101 inch</para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry valign="top" align="center">
                                    <para>1663011C1</para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry valign="top" align="center">
                                    <para>.102 to .145 inch</para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry valign="top" align="center">
                                    <para>1663010C1</para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                            <row>
                                <entry valign="top" align="center">
                                    <para>.146 inch and up</para>
                                </entry>
                                <entry valign="top" align="center">
                                    <para>Replace caliper and/or anchor plate (See Note)</para>
                                </entry>
                            </row>
                        </tbody>
                    </tgroup>
                </table>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>If the bumper gap exceeds .145, it will be necessary to replace the caliper or anchor plate or
                        both. To determine which component must be replaced, remove the caliper and replace with a new
                        caliper and re-measure gap. If the bumper gap with the new caliper is between .058 and .145
                        inch, select the proper shim from the above table (
                        <hotlnk xrefid="t9204012">
                            <emph type="bold">Table 2</emph>)
                        </hotlnk>
                        . If bumper gap with the new caliper exceeds .145 inch, replace anchor plate also.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Lubricate the sliding surfaces (V-ways) (
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9204011">Figure 1</hotlnk>) with special NLGI #1-1/2 lubricant (refer to
                    <hotlnk xrefid="t9204011">PARTS INFORMATION</hotlnk>
                    for the part number).
                    <emph type="bold">ANTI-SEIZE OR NEVERSEEZ ARE NOT RECOMMENDED SUBSTITUTES FOR NLGI #1-1/2
                        LUBRICANT.
                    </emph>
                </para>
            </step1>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Position shim as illustrated in
                    <hotlnk xrefid="f9204011">Figure 1</hotlnk>
                    on opposite side from support key. Hold shim in position and install caliper.
                </para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <important>
                    <para>DO NOT attempt to use more than one shim.</para>
                </important>
            </specpara>
            <step1>
                <para count="1">Install
                    <emph type="bold">NEW</emph>
                    support key and support spring, and install new key retaining bolt (supplied in Caliper Key kit).
                    Tighten bolt to 12-18 ft-lbs. (17-24 Nm).
                </para>
            </step1>
            <specpara>
                <note>
                    <para>A copy of this TSI letter should be attached to Service Manual Section CTS-5009 in the
                        CTS-5000 Master Service Manual. The manual section will be revised to include this information
                        at the next revision.
                    </para>
                </note>
            </specpara>
